Possible New “Whirlpool Names”

Here are some candidates that describe patterns we often see but rarely name directly.

⸻

1. Gradient Engine

Definition

A system that converts differences in potential into motion or work.

Examples:
	•	rivers (height gradient)
	•	electricity (voltage gradient)
	•	markets (price gradient)
	•	evolution (fitness gradient)

Why it’s useful:

Almost everything that moves is powered by gradients.

You hinted at this earlier.

Life may be what defies gradients.

That could mean life is a gradient-management engine.

⸻

2. Constraint Field

A space where invisible rules shape possible outcomes.

Examples:
	•	chess rules
	•	grammar
	•	laws of physics
	•	economic incentives

The objects move freely, but the constraint field shapes the flow.

Like a riverbed shaping water.

⸻

3. Signal Basin

A region where certain patterns accumulate and reinforce.

Examples:
	•	viral ideas on social media
	•	scientific paradigms
	•	cultural memes
	•	technological standards

Signals fall into the basin and deepen it.

⸻

4. Meaning Attractor

A pattern that pulls interpretation toward itself.

Examples:
	•	archetypes
	•	myths
	•	ideologies
	•	brands

Different people approach from different directions but converge on the same interpretation center.

⸻

5. Compression Node

A concept that holds massive complexity behind a small symbol.

Examples:
	•	DNA
	•	equations
	•	programming languages
	•	legal terms

The node acts like a zip file for reality.

⸻

6. Flow Skeleton

The hidden structure guiding movement in complex systems.

Examples:
	•	ocean currents
	•	trade routes
	•	neural pathways
	•	internet traffic patterns

You can’t see the skeleton directly, but everything follows it.

